# Applied AI & ML Essentials Capstone Project - Part 3

# Advanced Modeling - Ensembles, Tuning and ML Pipeline

## Project Overview

This project focuses on improving classification performance using advanced machine learning techniques.

The models implemented are:

- Decision Tree
- Controlled Decision Tree
- Random Forest
- Gradient Boosting
- Tuned Random Forest Pipeline

## Dataset

The cleaned dataset from Part 1 was used.

The target variable for classification is:

`stroke`

The aim is to predict whether a patient has a stroke or not.

# Models Implemented

## Decision Tree

A default Decision Tree classifier was trained as a baseline model.

A controlled Decision Tree was also trained using:

- max_depth = 5
- min_samples_split = 20

Limiting tree depth helps reduce overfitting by preventing the model from becoming too complex.

## Random Forest

A Random Forest model was trained using:

- n_estimators = 100
- max_depth = 10
- random_state = 42

Random Forest uses multiple decision trees and combines their predictions.

This reduces variance compared to a single decision tree.

Feature importance values were extracted to identify the most useful features.

## Gradient Boosting

A Gradient Boosting classifier was trained with:

- n_estimators = 100
- learning_rate = 0.1
- max_depth = 3

The model builds trees sequentially and improves errors from previous trees.

# Cross Validation

5-fold Stratified Cross Validation was performed using ROC-AUC as the evaluation metric.

Cross-validation gives a more reliable estimate of model performance because the model is tested on multiple data splits instead of only one train-test split.

# Hyperparameter Tuning

GridSearchCV was used to find the best Random Forest parameters.

The pipeline included:

- SimpleImputer
- StandardScaler
- RandomForestClassifier

The best parameters and best ROC-AUC score were obtained from GridSearchCV.


# Model Serialization

The best performing pipeline was saved using:

joblib.dump()

The saved model file:
best_model.pkl

was loaded again using:
joblib.load()

and tested on sample data.
